    <h1 class="title">
      Single-Use. Safer Investment.
    </h1>
    <div class="content">
      <div class="left_section">
        <div class="container_top_left">
          <h3>
            Reusable bronchoscopes can be an unnecessary drain on hospital budgets.
          </h3>
          <p>
            On top of reprocessing costs, repairs, annual service contracts, and procedure delays when scopes aren’t available, costly infections still occur: $28,383 per treatment per case.<sup>1</sup>
          </p>
          <p>
            The misconception that single-use is too expensive only clouds the solution. Sterile single-use bronchoscopes like the GlideScope<sup>®</sup>
            BFlex<sup>tm</sup>
            can help facilities eliminate these extra costs and delays.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="container_bottom_left">
          <h2>
            Single-use bronchoscopes mean improved accessibility and safety
          </h2>
          <ul class="features">
            <li class="feature_item">
              <div class="feature_img icon1"></div>
              <div class="feature_item_content column9">
                <h4 class="feature_item_heading">Eliminate reprocessing costs</h4>
                <p class="description_light">
                  Single-use bronchoscopes don’t require reprocessing. Getting reusables patient-ready is extensive and time consuming: the cost for reprocessing one endoscope ranges from $50.14 to $152.66.<sup>2</sup>
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="feature_item">
              <div class="feature_img icon2"></div>
              <div class="feature_item_content column9">
                <h4 class="feature_item_heading">No expensive repairs</h4>
                <p class="description_light">
                  Damage to reusable bronchoscopes is possible during procedures and repairs can be expensive. One study cites $148 for repairs per use.<sup>3</sup>
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="feature_item">
              <div class="feature_img icon3"></div>
              <div class="feature_item_content column9">
                <h4 class="feature_item_heading">Minimize the risk of cross contamination</h4>
                <p class="description_light">
                  Single-use bronchoscopes can protect against infection. Multiple studies show that costly infections occur even when reprocessing exceeds national guidelines. The cost of treatment for each infection due to cross contamination and subsequent infection
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                is $28,383.<sup>4</sup>
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="feature_item">
              <div class="feature_img icon4"></div>
              <div class="feature_item_content">
                <h4 class="feature_item_heading">Avoid service contracts</h4>
                <p class="description_light">
                  Annual contract fees per bronchoscope add up and often exclude preventable damage, which can cost nearly the same in additional fees for out-of-pocket repairs and limit availability during off-site servicing.
                </p>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>

      </div>
      <div class="right_section">
        <div class="container_top_right">
          <p class="quote">
            To reduce patient exposure to contaminated bronchoscopes, institutions should consider shifting from HLD to sterilization.
          </p>
